                    "id": "BIO111E070",
                    "name": "AP Biology 11",
                    "track": "AP",
                    "description": "The AP Biology course is designed to be the equivalent of a college introductory course usually taken by biology majors during their first year. The course framework includes two essential components: science practices and course contents. Science practices are skills that are fundamental to the discipline of Biology, and students are trained to develop those skills during this course. Examples of science practices include concept explanation, visual representation, representation and describing data, etc. The course content is organized into eight units: chemistry of life, cell structure and function, cellular energetics, cell communication and cell cycle, heredity, gene expression and regulation, natural selection, and ecology. The goal of this course will be readiness for the study of advanced topics in subsequent college courses. All students enrolled in an AP subject must sit the external exam at the end of the school year.",
